🚀 1. What is a Read–Write Lock?

👉 A ReadWriteLock allows:

    ✅ Multiple threads to read simultaneously
    ❌ Only one thread to write at a time
    ❌ No read while writing
    🧠 Why not just synchronized?

Because synchronized:

    Only ONE thread at a time (even for reads) ❌
    👉 Read-heavy systems become slow

🔥 Solution
    Many readers OR one writer
    ⚙️ 2. Java Implementation

Java provides:

    👉 ReentrantReadWriteLock


🔍 4. Internal Behavior (VERY IMPORTANT)
🔹 Read Lock
    Multiple threads allowed
    Uses shared access

🔹 Write Lock
    Exclusive access
    Blocks:
    other writers ❌
    all readers ❌
🧠 Internal State (Simplified)
    readCount = number of readers
    writeOwner = thread holding write lock
🔥 5. Lock Rules
Scenario	            Allowed?
Read + Read	            ✅
Read + Write	        ❌
Write + Write	        ❌

⚠️ 6. Corner Cases (VERY IMPORTANT)
❗ 1. Writer Starvation

    👉 Too many readers:

    Readers keep coming → writer never gets chance ❌
    ✅ Fix: Fair Lock
    new ReentrantReadWriteLock(true);
    ❗ 2. Lock Downgrading (Allowed)

    👉 Write → Read

        lock.writeLock().lock();
        try {
            // modify

            lock.readLock().lock(); // acquire read before releasing write
        } finally {
            lock.writeLock().unlock();
        }
    ❗ 3. Lock Upgrading (NOT Allowed)

        👉 Read → Write

        lock.readLock().lock();
        lock.writeLock().lock(); // ❌ DEADLOCK risk
    ❗ 4. Deadlock Scenario
        Thread1: read → wants write
        Thread2: read → wants write
        → both stuck forever ❌
    ❗ 5. Forgetting unlock()

        👉 Causes system hang


⚔️ 8. ReadWriteLock vs Other Locks
Feature                 	ReadWriteLock	synchronized	ReentrantLock
Multiple readers	          ✅	            ❌	            ❌
Write exclusivity	          ✅	            ✅           	✅
Performance (read-heavy)    	🔥           	❌           	❌

🔥 9. Advanced: Reentrancy

👉 Same thread can re-acquire lock

lock.writeLock().lock();
lock.writeLock().lock(); // allowed

🧠 10. When to Use

Use ReadWriteLock when:

    ✅ Reads >> Writes
    ✅ Shared data structure
    ✅ High concurrency

❌ When NOT to Use

    ❌ Write-heavy systems
    ❌ Simple cases → use synchronized
    ❌ Risk of deadlocks

🔥 11. Performance Insight

👉 Best case:

    100 readers → all run in parallel 🚀

👉 Worst case:

Frequent writes → behaves like normal lock
🧠 12. Interview Answer (Perfect)

ReadWriteLock allows multiple readers but only one writer.
It improves performance in read-heavy systems by reducing contention while maintaining data consistency.